    "reasoning": "First, compute $ k = \\sqrt{4} - 1 $. Since $ \\sqrt{4} = 2 $, we have $ k = 2 - 1 = 1 $. Next, define $ \\beta = k - \\sqrt[3]{2} + \\sqrt[3]{4} = 1 - \\alpha + \\alpha^2 $ where $ \\alpha = \\sqrt[3]{2} $ (so $ \\alpha^3 = 2 $). To find the minimal monic polynomial with integer coefficients for $ \\beta $, express $ \\beta $ in terms of $ \\alpha $ and eliminate $ \\alpha $. Starting with $ \\beta = \\alpha^2 - \\alpha + 1 $, rearrange to $ \\alpha^2 = \\beta + \\alpha - 1 $. Multiply by $ \\alpha $: $ \\alpha^3 = \\beta\\alpha + \\alpha^2 - \\alpha $. Substitute $ \\alpha^3 = 2 $ and $ \\alpha^2 = \\beta + \\alpha - 1 $: $ 2 = \\beta\\alpha + (\\beta + \\alpha - 1) - \\alpha $, simplifying to $ \\beta\\alpha = 3 - \\beta $, so $ \\alpha = \\frac{3 - \\beta}{\\beta} $. Substitute into $ \\alpha^3 = 2 $: $ \\left( \\frac{3 - \\beta}{\\beta} \\right)^3 = 2 $. Expanding gives $ (3 - \\beta)^3 = 2\\beta^3 $, leading to $ 27 - 27\\beta + 9\\beta^2 - \\beta^3 = 2\\beta^3 $. Rearranging terms yields $ 3\\beta^3 - 9\\beta^2 + 27\\beta - 27 = 0 $, and dividing by 3 gives the monic polynomial $ \\beta^3 - 3\\beta^2 + 9\\beta - 9 = 0 $. This polynomial is irreducible over $ \\mathbb{Q} $ (no rational roots via Rational Root Theorem and degree 3), so it is minimal.",
